Kura 3.1.0, develop branch

Currently the ConfigurationServiceImpl creates and starts a ConfigurableServiceTracker.  Here's the source for ConfigurableComponentTracker:

https://github.com/eclipse/kura/blob/develop/kura/org.eclipse.kura.core.configuration/src/main/java/org/eclipse/kura/core/configuration/ConfigurableComponentTracker.java

The ConfigurableServiceTracker is created with this constructor code:

        // TODO: find a better filter
        // This works but we track everything
        super(context, context.createFilter("(" + Constants.OBJECTCLASS + "=*)"), null);

As it says in the comment this filter of objectClass=* means that every created service is tracked.   One consequence of this is that all services registered will have their context.getService(ref) method called by this tracker, whether or not they have any actual consumers.    This is wasteful and defeats the declarative services laziness.

Another consequence is that for extenders like OSGi Remote Service Admin and Blueprint, the calls to getService(ref) will fail (return null) because these extenders create proxies for the service, and they are specified to use the Bundle consumer (in this case org.eclipse.kura.core.configuration) to load the service interfaces classes.   Because the kura configuration bundle classloader does/will not have access to some service interfaces classes (e.g. those services created by apps, etc) it will be unable to call context.getService(ref) when these extenders are being used.

Ideally the ConfigurableServiceTracker should not track all services, but rather some subset (e.g. based upon service properties or service interfaces) of services in order to avoid creating spurious errors when proxies are created.

In `DeploymentPackageUninstallOptions.java` the following check is done:

```java
super.setJobId((Long) request.getMetric(METRIC_JOB_ID));
if (super.getJobId() == null) {
  throw new KuraInvalidMessageException("Missing jobId!");
}
```

However the parameter type of `setJobId` is actually `long` instead of `Long`. So instead of the `KuraInvalidMessageException` a NPE will be thrown here.

Beside that I don't see any ready to prefix every call with `super`.

Currently Kura doesn't properly report the fact that a download is "already done".

Kura directly adds the enum to the metric set:

```
    public static void downloadAlreadyDoneSyncMessage(KuraResponsePayload respPayload) {
        respPayload.setTimestamp(new Date());
        respPayload.addMetric(KuraNotifyPayload.METRIC_TRANSFER_SIZE, 0);
        respPayload.addMetric(KuraNotifyPayload.METRIC_TRANSFER_PROGRESS, 100);
        respPayload.addMetric(KuraNotifyPayload.METRIC_TRANSFER_STATUS, DOWNLOAD_STATUS.ALREADY_DONE);
    }
```

In the log file you can see:
```
16:39:04,321 [pool-3-thread-1] ERROR CloudPayloadProtoBufEncoderImpl:77  - During serialization, ignoring metric named: dp.download.status. Unrecognized value type: org.eclipse.kura.core.deployment.CloudDeploymentHandlerV2$DOWNLOAD_STATUS.
```

Beside that, Kapua doesn't understand this enum anyway. See eclipse/kapua#272

In `LinuxUdev.c:49` is a call to `exit()` in the case `udev` cannot be initialized.

``` c
udev = udev_new();
if (!udev) {
   printf("Can't create udev\n");
   exit(1);
}
```

IMHO exiting the JVM in such a very is a very, very bad idea. I think throwing an exception should be the way to go.

At `LinuxUdev.c:121` is the following code:

``` c
//add it to the ArrayList
jboolean jbool = (*env)->CallBooleanMethod(env, objArr, mid_add, UsbDeviceObject);
if (jbool == NULL) return NULL;
```

Which results in the case that if the item could not be added to the list, the function returns, not freeing the current element and not returning the list.

Beside that the boolean type should be checked against `JNI_FALSE`.

To me it looks like a copy and paste error from the code segments above where the "if" actually makes sense:

``` c
jobject objArr = (*env)->NewObject(env, arrayClass, mid_init);
if (objArr == NULL) return NULL;
```

Still those returns will leak resources.

The implementation of `ComponentMetaTypeBundleTracker` is overriding the `open` method an manually processing all bundles a second time during the `open` call. In the log file you can see that all bundles get processed twice. Once by the "adding" method (since the call to `super.open` comes first) and second by the open call itself.

``` java
    @Override
    public void open() {
        s_logger.info("Opening ComponentMetaTypeBundleTracker...");
        super.open();
        s_logger.debug("open(): getting bundles...");
        Bundle[] bundles = this.m_context.getBundles();
        if (bundles != null) {
            for (Bundle bundle : bundles) {
                if (bundle.getState() == Bundle.ACTIVE) {
                    s_logger.debug("open(): processing MetaType for bundle: {}...", bundle.getSymbolicName());
                    processBundleMetaType(bundle);
                    s_logger.debug("open(): processed MetaType for bundle: {}", bundle.getSymbolicName());
                } else {
                    s_logger.debug("open(): bundle: {} is in state: {}. MetaType will be processed by addingBundle()",
                            bundle.getSymbolicName(), bundle.getState());
                }
            }
        }
        s_logger.debug("open(): done");
    }
```

